 later twentieth-century thinkers who fused the studies of mass communications and public opinion research. Terry N. Clark’s introduction, considered the premier guide to Tarde’s opus, accompanies this important work, reprinted here for the first time in forty years.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aSocial influence. 0aSociologyxHistoryy19th century. 0aSociologyxHistoryy20th century. 0aSociology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  agabriel tarde, communication, social influence, sociology, sociological, sociologist, 19th century, france, french, translation, translated text, collective behavior, mass communications, civic opinions, patterns, societal change, economics, psychology, sociologism, emile durkheim, imitation, personality, attitude, public opinion, stratification, psychological interactions, innovation.1 aClark, Terry N.1 aClark, Terry N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClark, Terry N., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJanowitz, Morris.40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226789798423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226789798/original  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles